@realmoney A Glutton For Punishment? I am about one third through my Kraft Heinz analysis (I will be done next week). Based on the output thus far I am picking at the stock under $27/share. More next week. $KHC

If you carefully read my tweets of the day (when I quote Northman Trader) you will see that his are observations and not recommendations. Here is the archived list @realmoney realmoney.thestreet.com/find…
I agree

Guests like Howard Marks, Lee Cooperman, Stan Druckenmiller, Ken Langone are fountains of investment information that I learn from in everyone of their appearances. There are many others. Santoli, Faber, Keene, Q and others are objective and rigorous and have an understanding of
history.

You and I are skeptics - through and through. We are confident in our own methodologies and are rigorous in approach. We do hear from the best traders and investors in the biz media - we disagree on this. But my focus is on the other 95% we see that don't account or document ..

Finally you say "my own review is more impt than their records." @revshark that is a given (and is something that you, a pro, and I write about), but the networks cater to the retail investor that too often doesn't do his own homework and just responds to "professionals" -
taking less time to evaluate a stock than they would in buying a refrigerator.

Let's agree to disagree. My view is that there are numerous "talking heads" in biz media that are rigorous and provide value in their observations and ideas. You disagree, regardless of records. The problem is that, in the main, the average viewer cant evaluate the numerous

recommendations that are undocumented. Successful ideas are highlighted but the invt boners are too often swept under the rug. You feel it is cumbersome to record by the networks and think it is simple.

I respectfully disagree. Make a continuing chart with ideas, price and date recorded. You cant just throw 20+ investment ideas everyday and not provide an opportunity to evaluate their success (and value to viewers).
How else can a viewer make the determination that the panelists' ideas have value? How can you, Rev, evaluate which people you will listen to in the biz media if there is no record of perf?
recommendations if they are not memorialized? By personality? By degree of confidence of delivery? Not on your life.
All the networks have to do is assign performance compilation to an intern. Easey peasey. @RevShark They don't - unlike @realmoney, sell side analysts.

Rev 1. Before making that observation I would ask you to read my response to Tim Collins in our Comments Section of @realmoney Thanks. 2. I am not critical of the performance of people on CNBC. I am critical that the network (and others) don't memorialize the performance.

After all, how can viewers evaluate the value of those recommendations (that are plentiful) if we don't know how those recommendations performed. Look at comments section and get back to me! Enjoy the weekend.

I respectfully disagree my buddy, Tony. As I discuss in yesterday's @realmoney column (which you have) we can not dismiss untenable debt loads when they are already exhibiting a growth dulling impact on GDP (despite the fiscal and monetary largesse). realmoney.thestreet.com/doug…

From my analysis: To understand the severity of this problem we should look back into the 2001-07 cycle. During that period global debt rose by only $30 trillion (from $86 trillion to $116 trillion). In the interim interval, global GDP rose by $25 trillion to $58 trillion.

An Trading World in Disarray * Mr. Market is almost impossible to navigate on a day trading basis “Television is our chief tool in selling our policy.” - Richard Hass, A World In Disarray amazon.com/World-Disarray-Am… Given the "newsy" nature of the increasingly volatile markets,

the unpredictable behavior (and policies) of The Supreme Tweeter, the unusual global interest rate setting (which too many are taking for granted), the absence of coordination between the leading economic countries, the deepening manufacturing recession that appears to be seeping

into the services sector (creating the likelihood of more EPS disappointments, announcements and guidedowns in 3Q2019 and questions regarding central banks' ability to catalyze growth (the problem is not the availability and cost of capital) -- the short term market gyrations
seem likely to continue for some time to come in a market without memory from day to day.
Position trading ( 1-2 weeks) seems to be the ticket for the opportunistic and not day trading (1-2 days) -- considering the lack of day to day forecasting accuracy given the active role

of the above independent variables. Intermediate-term it still looks like, after an upside overshoot a month ago, that an important market top occurred in January, 2018. Long term, despite what John Maynard Keynes said, we will be fine! @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC
